i-step refinement (0.05), Workflow is the clear boundary (0.85).\n\nFor the test descriptions: Behavior 1 sends a natural language function description with explicit signature requirements to the LLM, calls the code generation service, extracts the generated signature, and verifies it matches expected parameters, types, and return type—running multiple times to account for LLM variability. Behavior 2 calls the service with a function description and test suite, verifies the service returns working code that passes all tests within 3 refinement attempts, executes the generated code against the test suite, and runs the test multiple times with different descriptions. Behavior 3 configures the service to generate failing code on the first attempt, verifies the failure, mocks the second LLM call to check that failure messages are included in the prompt, and asserts that failure details aren't truncated. Behavior 4 mocks the LLM to consistently return failing code\n\n, calls the service, verifies exactly 3 attempts are made, and validates the error response includes all attempts with their test results and timestamps. Behavior 5 selects a complex function description that typically fails on a single attempt, calls the service with test cases, executes the full refinement loop with the real LLM, verifies either a passing implementation or a structured error after 3 failures, and runs the test multiple times to confirm the service improves code quality across iterations.\n\nAll behaviors have `plan_consistent: true` since the test descriptions align with the minimum levels chosen. I'm reconsidering whether Behaviors 3 and 4 should be Integration or Unit level. For Behavior 3, Integration is most likely (70% probability) because the service needs to orchestrate the LLM call, test runner, and data flow between them—even with mocks, I'm testing the service's integration logic, not just isolated functions. For Behavior 4, Integration is similarly the right choice since I need to verify the service's error handling across the full attempt cycle.\n\nActually, I'm second-guessing Behavior 3. To verify that failure messages get passed to the next LLM prompt, I can mock the LLM on both attempts and capture what's sent—this is entirely testable within a single process using function calls and mocks, which suggests Unit level. But I could also test it at Integration level by calling the service end-to-end. The question is whether the minimum viable test requires real infrastructure or just mocks. Since I can verify the behavior with mocks alone, Unit level seems sufficient. level (real test runner).\n\nThe honest minimum is **Unit**, but practically **Integration** makes more sense. Let me reconsider the level definitions: Unit tests one local function with no I/O, while Integration tests several modules wired together. Even with mocks, verifying that the refinement loop correctly passes failure messages between the LLM caller and test runner requires testing these components as an integrated system. So I'm setting Behavior 3 to **Integration**.\n\nNow I can finalize the test levels: Behavior 1 and 2 are **Agentic**, Behaviors 3 and 4 are **Integration**, and Behavior 5 is **Workflow**. Time to structure the output.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":13600,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":13600},"output_tokens":4,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"dc1dfee2-11e8-4101-b44f-c51387c6d9d5","uuid":"74ffa13c-816d-4b56-b5d8-5b914d1046b5"}
